ve to new institutional economics and the rational choice approach, Boldizzoni builds on the extraordinary accomplishments of twentieth-century European historians and social thinkers to offer fresh ideas for the renewal of the field. Economic history needs to rediscover the true relationship between economy and culture, and promote an authentic alliance with the social sciences, starting with sociology and anthropology. It must resume its dialogue with the humanities, but without shrinking away from theory when constructing its models. The Poverty of Clio demonstrates why history must exert its own creative power on economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomicsxHistory. 0aEconomicsxResearchxMethodology. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aDouglass North.  aKarl Polanyi.  aMoses Finley.  aWitold Kula.  acliometrics.  acultural history.  aculture.  aeconomic history.  aeconomic reasoning.  aeconomic system.  aeconomic theory.  aeconomy.  aindividualism.  ainstitutional approach.  aintellectual crisis.  amaterialism.  amedieval economics.  aneoclassical economics.  aneoclassical microeconomics.  aneoliberal economics.  apast generations.  apolicy recommendations.  asocial history.  asocial science history.  asocial science.  auniversality.  aworldviews.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400838851zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400838851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400838851.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_E